```javascript
function merge(a, b) {
  const isPlain = v => v && typeof v === "object" && !Array.isArray(v);
  const out = isPlain(a) ? { ...a } : {};
  for (const k in b) {
    out[k] = isPlain(b[k]) && isPlain(out[k]) ? merge(out[k], b[k]) : b[k];
  }
  return out;
}
```

Why this doesn't mutate `a`: every level starts a new object (`{ ...a }`), and when a key needs deep merging we recurse and **reassign** `out[k]` to the freshly returned object — we never write into a shared nested object like `out.nested.q = …`. So `a` and all its branches are left untouched.

